				\begin{document}$$ {\text{CO}}_{2} + {\text{H}}_{2} \to {\text{CO + H}}_{2} {\text{O}} $$\end{document}can be used, in concert with catalysts (copper-, iron-, or ceria-based systems), to convert CO2 and hydrogen to CO and water. The CO mixed with hydrogen produces syngas, which can be used to generate a variety of products, including methanol, or liquid hydrocarbons through Fischer–Tropsch synthesis [77]. Issues related to the thermal stability of the catalysts and the undesired formation of methane still need to be resolved. There are also direct routes for hydrogenating CO2 to make products including methanol, methane, and formic acid. Besides these hydrogenation routes, CO2 can also, in principle, be converted to fuels using direct solar energy through electro-catalytic, photo-electrochemical, and thermochemical reduction, although these approaches remain in very early stages of development.
